  %h4 How Bash Uses Aliases/Commands
  %p First, it will try to find an alias for the given name. &nbsp;If no alias is found, then it will use the first command in your $PATH by the given name.
  %h3 Scenario
  %p
    You set default options for
    %strong cmd-x
    by creating an alias with the same name (
    %strong> cmd-x
    ). &nbsp;In this example, the alias and command are both called “grep”.
  %pre $&gt; alias grep="grep --color"
  %p
    %strong BUT!
    \&nbsp;What if you want to run grep&nbsp;
    %strong without
    the “–color” option?
  %h3 Solution #1: Wrap the command name in quotes
  %pre $&gt; "grep" #...
  %p
    This is the same situation as
    = succeed "." do
      %a{:href => "http://wp.me/p2MUFm-1u"} Solution #0
    \&nbsp;There aren’t any aliases that match “grep” (with quotes). &nbsp;Also, “grep” wrapped in quotes is just a string that evaluations to grep. &nbsp;The shell will then find grep in our $PATH and run it normally.
